In order to fetch the data from the database, sql queries were written to retrieve the Salaries and Teams information and then read into pandas dataframe. The two dataframes were merged together to have the payroll information and win percentage in one dataframe. The dataframe df does outer join on the two dataframes, and it has several missing values that did not match between the two dataframes. There are no missing values in teams and salaries dataframe as shown above. One of the reasons for NaN values in df is that the Teams table had data for a longer time period compared to the Salaries table, so when they were joined on yearID and teamID, there were several rows that had NaN in sum_salary and avg_salary column. The dataframe df_filtered does inner join on the two dataframes, and thus, any non-matching values on teamID or yearID column are filtered out. The df_filtered is particularly useful when plotting regression lines for analysis, since SVD may not converge if there are NaNs present in the datapoints.

for i in range(len(team_names)):
    team_info = sub_df.loc[df['teamID']== team_names[i]] # dataframe filtered with specific team name
    team_info.sort_values("yearID", ascending=True) # sort the dataframe by years

    year = team_info.loc[team_info['sum_salary']== max_salary]['yearID'] # get the year correspnding with max salary for annotation x coordinate

The dataframe was filtered to get observations whose yearID is greater than or equal to 1990. Data for each team was fetched from the dataframe and visualized using total payroll over time from 1990 to 2014 as shown in the figure above. The team names were labelled on location where max payroll occurred for the respective teams.

Question 1¶

The plot above illustrates the total payroll of the teams present between 1990-2014. It demonstrates a general trend of payroll increasing over time. Further, it is interesting to note that total payroll of the teams were very close around 1990-1995, and over time we see them spreading apart. There are distinct outliers like NYA, PHI and LAN that have significantly increased their spending. There are also some teams that have significantly cut down their spendings in recent years. However, the mean payroll seems to be increasing over time since there are more outliers that are pulling it towards higher payroll total. Additionally, the range of the payroll is also increasing over the years.

In [62]:
bins = [1985,1991,1997,2003,2009,2015] # create bins to divide the years into five time periods
cols = ['1985-1990','1991-1996','1997-2002','2003-2008','2009-2014'] # label the bins
partition = pandas.cut(df_filtered['yearID'], bins, right=False,labels=cols) # partition the data based on bins
df_filtered['partition'] = partition # add a partition column to dataframe
df_partition = df_filtered.groupby('partition') # group by the partition

count = 0 # keeps track of bin value
for j in range(0, 5): # create five plots for each time period
    plt.figure()
    group = df_partition.get_group(cols[count]) # get the grouping for each time period
    team_names = group.teamID.unique() # get the teams present in the time period
    x_val = [] # keeps track of x values to plot
    y_val = [] # keeps track of corresponding y values to plot
    for i in range(len(team_names)): # for each team present in the time period
        team_info = group.loc[group['teamID']== team_names[i]] # get all the information about that team
        avg_salary = team_info['sum_salary'].mean() # avg salary for the team across the time period
        avg_win = team_info['win_percentage'].mean() # avg win percentage for the across the time period
        x_val.append(avg_salary) # add the x data point
        y_val.append(avg_win) # add the y data point
        plt.annotate(team_names[i], (avg_salary + 0.1, avg_win)) # add team label to each data point
        plt.scatter(avg_salary, avg_win)
        plt.title('Win Percentage Vs Payroll Averaged over '+ str(cols[count]))
    plot_df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(x_val, y_val))) # create a dataframe containing all the salary avgerage and win average for each team in the time period           
    slope, intercept = np.polyfit(plot_df[0], plot_df[1], 1) # find slope and intercept to plot the regression line
    points = np.linspace(plot_df[0].min(), plot_df[0].max(),100) # create the x data points
    plt.plot(points, slope*points+intercept, color='r') # plot the regression line
    plt.xlabel('Average Payroll')
    plt.ylabel('Average Win Percentage')
    count += 1 
    plt.figure

The dataframe containing information about average salary and win percentage for teams from 1985-2014 is partitioned into five time periods (1985-1990, 1991-1996, 1997-2002, 2003-2008, 2009-2014). For each team present during a time period, the total payroll and win percentage of the team is averaged over that time period and plotted. Accordingly, each time period is plotted as shown above. yearID before 1985 have NaN values for average salary as mentioned in part 1. Thus, for our analysis, those NaN values provide no use and are eliminated.

Question 2¶

The plot above illustrates win percentage over payroll averaged over a time period for each team. It demonstrates a positive correlation between average payroll and win percentage, which means as the average payroll increases so does the average win percentage. For example, NYA spends the most from 1991-2014 and their winning percentage is one of the largest. They have more than or to equal to the expected number of wins during those periods. However, there are also outliers, especially in the early years, that have spent large amount of money for that time period but not achieved expected number of wins. For example, ATL, LAN, CHN in 1985-1990 and NYN, DET, SFN in 1991-1996 and BAL, TEX, LAN in 1997-2002. Roughly starting at 2003, teams that were spending less were also able to acheive good winning figures. For example, OAK has more than 50% win despite not spending very much compared to other teams during that time period, which means they were spending their money efficiently. In the most recent period (2009-2014), there are many teams such as OAK, TBA, ATL, CIN, etc. that are spending judiciously and achieving more than 50% winning rate. Across the time period, OAK seems to be one of the teams particularly good at paying for wins. Apart from the 1991-1996 period, OAK has achieved more wins than predicted by the regression line. Additionally, over time OAK spent less compared to other teams in that period but their winning percentage remained good, which means they learnt how to spend their money efficiently. Lastly, a limitation of the plots above is that it is difficult to compare plots over different time periods as the average payroll scale is different for each time period.

standard_dev_dict = {} # keep track of standard deviation for each year
avg_dict = {} # keep track of mean for each year
yearIDs = df_filtered.yearID.unique() # get the year IDs
# For each year, compute the mean and standard deviation of total payroll 
for i in yearIDs:
    avg_dict[i] = df_filtered.loc[df_filtered['yearID']== i]['sum_salary'].mean()
    standard_dev_dict[i] = df_filtered.loc[df_filtered['yearID']== i]['sum_salary'].std()

standardized_payroll = []
# Compute the standardized payroll for each payroll value present in the dataframe
for index, row in df_filtered.iterrows():
    group = row['yearID'] # get the year 
    salary = row['sum_salary'] # get the payroll value
    standardized_payroll.append((salary - avg_dict[group]) / standard_dev_dict[group]) # compute standardize payroll based on the year
df_filtered['standardized_payroll'] = standardized_payroll
df_filtered

The standardized payroll column was added to the dataframe. In order to calculate the standardize payroll, average payroll and standard deviation of the payroll (sum_salary) per year were calculated. For each entry in the dataframe, the payroll was taken and the average payroll of the correponding year was subtracted from it. The difference was then divided by standard deviation of the corresponding year to get the standardized payroll. This process standardizes the average payroll scale across the time periods.

Question 3¶

The plots illustrate the relationship between standardized payroll and win percentage. Similar to problem 4 analysis, there seems to be a positive correlation between standardized payroll and win percentage. The plots of problem 4 and 6 look the same but the x-axis in problem 6 is standardized. It now measures the distance from mean payroll for each team, where positive number indicates payroll is higher than mean payroll and negative indicates it's lower than mean payroll. As mentioned before, one of the limitations of plots in problem 4 is that each time period has different average payroll scale, which makes it difficult to compare plots across time. However, standardizing the scale remedies this problem as now they have the same units. A limitation of the plots above is that we can't see the actual payroll values.

# calculate the efficiency column
efficiency = []
for index, row in df_filtered.iterrows():
    win_percentage = row['win_percentage']
    salary = row['standardized_payroll']
    efficiency.append(win_percentage - (50 + 2.5 * salary))
df_filtered['efficiency'] = efficiency

team_names = ['OAK', 'BOS', 'NYA', 'ATL', 'TBA'] # team names
plt.figure() 
for i in range(len(team_names)):
    team_info = df_filtered.loc[df_filtered['teamID']== team_names[i]] # dataframe filtered with specific team name
    team_info.sort_values("yearID", ascending=True) # sort the dataframe by years
    plt.plot(team_info["yearID"], team_info["efficiency"]) # plot the efficieny vs year for each team
    max_salary = team_info["efficiency"].max() # get the max efficiency for annotation y coordinate
    year = team_info.loc[team_info['efficiency']== max_salary]['yearID'] # get the year correspnding with max efficiency for annotation x coordinate
    plt.annotate(team_names[i], (year, max_salary))


plt.title('Efficiency over the years')
plt.xlabel('Years')
plt.ylabel('Efficiency')
plt.show()

The regression line in problem 7 gives the expected number of win percentage as a function of standardized payroll. Looking at the regression line, it looks like teams that spend roughly the average payroll in a given year will win 50% of their games, and teams increase 5% wins for every 2 standard units of payroll. Using this generalization, we can calcuate the expected win percentage as 50 + 2.5 * standardized payroll, where standardized payroll is considered for each team per year. To calculate spending efficiency, we can subtract the expected win percentage from the corresponding win percentage for each observation in the dataframe. After adding the efficiency column in the dataframe, the efficiency was plotted over time from 1985-2014 for 5 teams (OAK, BOS, NYA, ATL, TBA). From the plot, it can be interpreted that the spending efficiency for the 5 teams fluctuates a lot. There is no distinct pattern of efficiency change over time. It is also possible that external factors contribute to these fluctuations that are not being taken into account here.

Question 4¶

From plots in question 2 and 3, it can be inferred that teams that spent more money tend to have higher number of win percentage (with some outliers). This plot of efficiency over time brings in an interesting perspective by showing that spending more money doesn't necessarily mean that teams are utilizing their money efficiently on getting the wins. For example, NYA from 1997-2014 spent the most money and recieved higher number of win percentage, but this plot shows that they have not been spending their money efficiently overall. The smart teams spend money on talented players to get results that are worth their investments. An example of this is OAK. The moneyball period took place around 2002 and the efficiency plot shows a peak for OAK around that time period, which means that they spent their money smartly and accordingly achieved good winning figures. Additionally, this plot provides a per year analysis of OAK efficiency illustrating that it tends to fluctuate a lot. This information was not evident in plots for question 2 and 3 as it provided an averaged view over each time period.

win_df = pd.DataFrame()
# get number of wins and losses for 2015-2022
for i in range(2015, 2022):
    page = reqs.get('https://www.espn.com/mlb/standings/_/season/'+ str(i) + '/group/overall')
    soup = BeautifulSoup(page.content, 'html5lib')
    table = soup.findAll('table')
    temp_df = pd.read_html(table[1].prettify())[0]
    team_scrape = soup.findAll('abbr')
    teamID = []
    team_name = []
    # regex to find the team ID
    regex = r"^<.+>(?P<id>[A-Z]+)"
    # regex to find the team name
    regex2 = r"^<.+title=\"(.+)\".+"
    for j in team_scrape:
        m = re.search( regex, str(j))
        teamID.append(m.groups('id')[0])
        m = re.search( regex2, str(j))
        team_name.append(m.groups('id')[0])
    temp_df['teamID'] = teamID # add team ID column
    temp_df['yearID'] = i # add year column
    temp_df['Team Name'] = team_name # add team name column 
    # calculate the win percentage and add its column
    temp_df['win_percentage'] = (temp_df['W'].astype('float')/(temp_df['W'].astype('float') + temp_df['L'].astype('float'))) * 100
    # add total win column
    temp_df['win'] = temp_df['W'].astype('int')
    # add total games column 
    temp_df['games'] = (temp_df['W'].astype('int') + temp_df['L'].astype('int'))
    # put the data for each year in one big dataframe
    win_df = win_df.append(temp_df, ignore_index=True)
# drop extraneous columns
win_df = win_df.drop('L', axis = 1)
win_df = win_df.drop('W', axis = 1)

conn.close() # close the first connection
# create a new database
conn = sqlite3.connect('updated_database')
c = conn.cursor()

# add table
c.execute('CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS full_table (teamID text, yearID number, sum_salary number, avg_salary number, win_percentage number, win number, games number)')
conn.commit()

# convert the dataframe to sQL and add it in the database
full_database.to_sql('full_table', conn, if_exists='replace', index = False)

# Check if the database is correctly populated
query = "SELECT * FROM full_table"
data = pandas.read_sql(query, conn)
conn.close() # close the second connection
